Based on the provided Tundra source code and expected results, it seems lik
like there is a logical issue in your if statements. If `request.enabled` i
is true then if `request.priority > 5` should print "skip" not "queue". Con
Conversely, if `request.enabled` is false it should print "disabled", not "
"queue". 

Here's the corrected Tundra source code:

```tundra
val request = {
  enabled: true,
  priority: 9
};

if (request.enabled) {
  if (request.priority > 5) {
    print("skip");
  } else {
    print("queue");
  }
} else {
  print("disabled");
}
```

This should now correctly print "disabled" when `request.enabled` is false,
false, and "skip" if both conditions are met (i.e., request.enabled = true 
AND request.priority > 5).
